Path: godot/tutorials/ui/gui_skinning.rst
Summary: Explains that the Theme resource drives the skinning system and how the default theme provides the base look for control nodes.
The skinning system is driven by the Theme resource. Every Godot project has an inherent default theme that contains the settings used by the built-in control nodes. This is what gives the controls their distinct look out of the box. A theme only describes the configuration, however, and it is still the job of each individual control to use that configuration in the way it requires to display itself. This is important to remember when implementing your own custom controls. Note: Even the Godot editor itself relies on the default theme. But it doesn't look the same as a Godot project, because it applies its own heavily customized theme on top of the default one. In principle, this works exactly like it would in your game as explained below.
---CHUNK---
Document: GUI Skinning
Path: godot/tutorials/ui/gui_skinning.rst
Summary: This section describes the different types of theme items used in Godot's GUI skinning system.
Theme items are the configurable elements within a theme, each identified by a unique name and belonging to a specific data type.

The available theme item types are:

*   **Color**: A Color value, used for text, backgrounds, and control/icon modulation.
*   **Constant**: An integer value, used for numeric control properties (e.g., item separation in BoxContainer) or boolean flags (e.g., drawing relationship lines in Tree).
*   **Font**: A Font resource, used by text-displaying controls. Fonts manage text rendering settings except size and color; alignment and text direction are controlled by individual controls.
*   **Font size**: An integer value, used with a Font to set the text display size.
*   **Icon**: A Texture2D resource, typically used for displaying icons on controls like Buttons.
*   **StyleBox**: A StyleBox resource, which defines how a UI panel is displayed. StyleBoxes are used by various controls for backgrounds and overlays, not just Panel.

Key Rule: Focus styleboxes are drawn as an overlay on top of other styleboxes (like normal or pressed), meaning they should be designed as outlines or translucent boxes to ensure the base stylebox remains visible.
---CHUNK---
Document: GUI Skinning
Path: godot/tutorials/ui/gui_skinning.rst
Summary: Explains how theme items are organized into types and how child classes inherit theme properties.

Theme items are organized into types, and each item must belong to a single type. An item is defined by its name, data type, and theme type, and this combination must be unique within a theme. For instance, two color items named "font_color" cannot exist in the same "Label" type, but one can exist in a "LineEdit" type.

The default Godot theme includes predefined theme types for every built-in control node that uses UI skinning. The specific items available for each control and its child classes can be found in the "Theme Properties" section of the class reference.

Note: Child classes can utilize theme items defined for their parent classes. For example, "Button" and its derivatives can use parent-defined items. While any control can technically use any theme item, this is generally avoided for clarity. For child classes, this inheritance is automated: when a built-in control requests a theme item, it can omit the theme type, and its class name will be used instead. Parent class names are also checked in sequence, allowing changes to a parent class like "Button" to affect all derived classes without individual customization.

Custom theme types can be defined, allowing customization of both built-in and custom controls. Since built-in controls are unaware of custom theme types, scripts are necessary for accessing these items. All control nodes provide methods to fetch theme items from their applied theme, accepting the theme type as an argument.

GDScript:
var accent_color = get_theme_color("accent_color", "MyType")
label.add_theme_color_override("font_color", accent_color)

C#:
Color accentColor = GetThemeColor("accent_color", "MyType");
label.AddThemeColorOverride("font_color", accentColor);

Theme types can be linked as variations to offer more customization. For example, a "Header" type can be a variation of the "Label" type. If a "Label" control is set to use the "Header" variation, this variation will be prioritized when requesting theme items. This enables storing multiple presets of theme items for the same control node class within a single "Theme" resource.

Warning: Only variations from the default theme or the custom project theme appear in the Inspector dock. Manually entering a variation name defined elsewhere is possible, but it is recommended to keep all variations within the project theme for consistency.

Further details on creating and using theme type variations can be found in a dedicated article.
---CHUNK---
